{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628832"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17241"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17241"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9931"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77900"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9931"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63378"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10698"},{"type":"tags","id":"10704"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23294"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77900"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring DNA replication, a point mutation occurs in a protein-coding gene, changing the codon GAA to GAG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReference: Genetic code\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAAA, AAG: Lysine (Lys)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAAC, AAT: Asparagine (Asn)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EACA, ACC, ACG, ACT: Threonine (Thr)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAGA, AGG: Arginine (Arg)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAGC, AGT: Serine (Ser)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EATA, ATC, ATT: Isoleucine (Ile)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EATG: Methionine (Met)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECAA, CAG: Glutamine (Gln)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECAC, CAT: Histidine (His)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECCA, CCC, CCG, CCT: Proline (Pro)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECGA, CGC, CGG, CGT: Arginine (Arg)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECTA, CTC, CTG, CTT: Leucine (Leu)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGAA, GAG: Glutamic acid (Glu)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGAC, GAT: Aspartic acid (Asp)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGCA, GCC, GCG, GCT: Alanine (Ala)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGGA, GGC, GGG, GGT: Glycine (Gly)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGTA, GTC, GTG, GTT: Valine (Val)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETAC, TAT: Tyrosine (Tyr)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETCA, TCC, TCG, TCT: Serine (Ser)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETGC, TGT: Cysteine (Cys)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETGG: Tryptophan (Trp)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETTA, TTG: Leucine (Leu)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETTC, TTT: Phenylalanine (Phe)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of this mutation on the encoded protein?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Substitution of glutamic acid with glycine","No change in amino acid sequence","Formation of a premature stop codon","Insertion of glutamic acid","Removal of glutamic acid"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis mutation results in \u003Cstrong\u003Eno change in amino acid sequence\u003C/strong\u003E because both GAA and GAG code for glutamic acid. This is an example of a synonymous mutation, also known as a silent mutation, where the change in DNA sequence does not affect the resulting amino acid sequence due to multiple codons encoding the same amino acid (genetic code redundancy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstitution of glutamic acid with glycine\u003C/strong\u003E - Both GAA and GAG code for glutamic acid, so no substitution occurs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of a premature stop codon\u003C/strong\u003E - Neither GAA nor GAG are stop codons\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsertion of glutamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E - Point mutations cannot add amino acids; this would require insertion of three nucleotides\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoval of glutamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E - Point mutations cannot delete amino acids; this would require deletion of three nucleotides\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile synonymous mutations do not change the amino acid sequence, they can still affect protein expression through changes in mRNA stability, translation speed, or protein folding dynamics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Synonymous mutations change the DNA sequence but result in the same amino acid due to redundancy in the genetic code.","While synonymous mutations do not alter protein sequence, they can affect mRNA stability, translation speed, and protein folding.","Multiple codons can specify the same amino acid due to the degeneracy of the genetic code."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63378"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17241"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63378"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:26:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:28:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9931"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77900"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67",